TermsBold:"AWS Builder Terms",createASpaceBold:"Create a space",createBold:"Create",note:"All spaces created are reviewed by our AI moderation tooling and are subject to the {{awsBuilderTermsBold}}. Violations of these terms will prohibit creation.",option1Step1:"Choose {{plusBold}} on the Builder Center top navigation and choose {{createASpaceBold}}.",option1Step2:"Populate the required details for your new space.",option1Step3:"Choose {{previewBold}} to review what your space will look like when live.",option1Step4:"Then choose {{createBold}}.",option1Title:"Option 1: From the top navigation",option2Step1:"Go to the Builder spaces landing page (Connect > Builder spaces)",option2Step2:"Choose {{createASpaceBold}}.",option2Step3:"Populate the required details for your new space.",option2Step4:"Choose {{previewBold}} to review what your space will look like when live.",option2Step5:"Then choose {{createBold}}.",option2Title:"Option 2: From the Builder Spaces landing page",plusBold:"+",previewBold:"Preview",question:"How do I create a space?"},howToJoinSpace:{answer:"There are three ways to join a space depending on the space type.",inviteOnlySpacesBold:"Invite-only spaces",invitesAndRequestsTabBold:"Invites and requests tab",joinBold:"Join",option1Description:"For all space types (public, private, and invite-only), you may receive a membership invite to join a space. The invitation will appear on the Builder spaces landing page under the {{invitesAndRequestsTabBold}}.",option1Title:"Option 1: Receive an invitation",option2Description:"{{publicSpacesBold}}: Choose {{joinBold}} from the space's detail page or from the Builder Spaces landing page and automatically become a member of the space.",option2Title:"Option 2: Click to join",option3Description:"{{privateSpacesBold}}: Choose {{joinBold}} from the space's detail page or from the Builder Spaces landing page to send a request to join the space. The admins and owner for the space will approve or decline your request. You will receive a notification for all approved requests.",option3InviteOnlyDescription:"{{inviteOnlySpacesBold}}: You cannot request to join invite-only spaces.",option3Title:"Option 3: Request to join",privateSpacesBold:"Private spaces",publicSpacesBold:"Public spaces",question:"How do I join a space?"},howToManageSpace:{answer:"As an admin or owner, there are different ways to manage a space:",archiveBold:"Archive",archiveOption1Step1:"Choose the title to open the space detail page.",archiveOption1Step2:"Choose the {{threeStackedDotsBold}} next to the space you own and select {{archiveBold}}.",archiveOption1Title:"Option 1: from the Builder spaces landing page",archiveOption2Step1:"Choose the title to open the space detail page.",archiveOption2Step2:"Choose the {{threeStackedDotsBold}} and select {{archiveBold}}.",archiveOption2Title:"Option 2: from the space detail page",archiveSpaceDescription:"Find the space you own and want to archive (Connect > Builder spaces > Your spaces tab).",archiveSpaceTitle:"Archive your space (Owner only)",editBold:"Edit",editOption1Step1:"Choose the {{threeStackedDotsBold}} next to the space and select {{editBold}}.",editOption1Step2:"Make desired changes.",editOption1Step3:"Choose {{saveBold}}.",editOption1Title:"Option 1: from the Builder spaces landing page",editOption2Step1:"Choose the title to open the space detail page.",editOption2Step2:"Choose the {{threeStackedDotsBold}} and select {{editBold}}.",editOption2Step3:"Make desired changes.",editOption2Step4:"Choose {{saveBold}}.",editOption2Title:"Option 2: from the space detail page",editSpaceDescription:"Find the space you own and want to edit:",editSpaceTitle:"Edit your space",grantRemoveAdminStep1:"Go to the space detail page and select the {{memberTabBold}}.",grantRemoveAdminStep2:"Choose the {{threeStackedDotsBold}} next to the member and select {{editBold}}.",grantRemoveAdminStep3:"Make desired changes.",grantRemoveAdminStep4:"Choose {{saveBold}}.",grantRemoveAdminTitle:"Grant / remove admin access (Owner only)",memberTabBold:"Member tab",question:"How do I manage a space as an admin or owner?",saveBold:"Save",threeStackedDotsBold:"three stacked dots"},whatAreBuilderSpaces:{answer:"Builder Spaces is a dynamic, virtual place that connects you and AWS builders around shared interests, experiences, and goals. Spaces help you create, manage, and join meaningful AWS communities online. Whether you're digitizing an in-person group, organizing events, or building a new virtual community, Spaces provide the tools you need. Choose the community style that works for you. Inside a {{publicBold}}, {{privateBold}} or {{inviteOnlyBold}} space, you can share ideas through posts, engage in discussions, and connect with like-minded individuals.",inviteOnlyBold:"invite-only",privateBold:"private",publicBold:"public",question:"What are Builder spaces?"},whatAreRoleTypes:{adminBold:"Admin",adminsBold:"Admins",adminsDetail:"{{adminsBold}} are members who receive additional space privileges from the space owner, including enforcing space rules, managing membership, and editing space details. Admins help to manage space membership.",answer:"There are 3 role types: {{memberBold}}, {{adminBold}}, and {{ownerBold}}.",awsBuilderCenterModeratorsBold:"AWS Builder Center moderators",awsBuilderTermsBold:"AWS Builder Terms",memberBold:"Member",membersBold:"Members",membersDetail:"{{membersBold}} are builders who have joined a public, private, or invite-only space. They have basic participation rights, must follow space rules, and can report inappropriate content but lack moderation powers. Members can report violations of the AWS Builder Terms to the AWS Builder Center moderators for review.",ownerBold:"Owner",ownersBold:"Owners",ownersDetail:"{{ownersBold}} are the original creators of a space and maintain sole, non-transferable ownership. They are responsible for managing all aspects of the space, including enforcing rules, maintaining quality, managing admins, and overseeing membership and invites to ensure the space fulfills its purpose. Owners are the only role allowed to archive the space.",question:"What are the different role types in a space?"},whatAreSpaceRules:{answer:"Space rules are created and enforced by the Space's owners and admins. Rules are created for each space to align with the space's purpose. Builder Center moderators are not responsible for enforcing space rules.",question:"What are space rules and who enforces them?"},whatAreSpaceTypes:{answer:"There are three space types: {{publicBold}}, {{privateBold}}, and {{inviteOnlyBold}}.",builderModerationTeamBold:"Builder Moderation team",inviteOnlyBold:"invite-only",inviteOnlyDetail:"{{inviteOnlySpacesBold}} represent the most exclusive and restricted space type. These spaces are completely hidden from general discovery and can only be accessed through direct invitations from admins or owners. Once set as invite-only, this designation is permanent and cannot be changed to public or private.",inviteOnlySpacesBold:"Invite-only spaces",note:"All spaces will be accessible to the {{builderModerationTeamBold}}.",privateBold:"private",privateDetail:"{{privateSpacesBold}} require membership approval from the owner or admin. While anyone can discover and request to join private spaces, only members can view the space's content and member list. Private spaces can be changed to an {{inviteOnlyBold}} space.",privateSpacesBold:"Private spaces",publicBold:"public",publicDetail:"{{publicSpacesBold}} are the most open and accessible type of Builder Space. Anyone can view and join public spaces. The space's content, member list, and discussions are visible to anyone who is signed in, even before joining. Public spaces can be changed to {{privateBold}} or {{inviteOnlyBold}} spaces.",publicSpacesBold:"Public spaces",question:"What are the different space types?",verifiedNote:"Any space that is marked as verified will be managed by an AWS team and appear with a verified badge {{verifiedIcon}} next to the space name."}},title:"Builder spaces"},spaceActions:{active:"ACTIVE",adminActions:"Admin actions",invitesAndRequests:"Invites and requests",ownerActions:"Owner actions",suspended:"SUSPENDED"},spaceComponents:{spaceActionButton:{joined:"Joined",signInModal:{bodyText:"Sign in to Builder Center to join this space.",headerText:"Join this space"}},spaceAside:{aboutThisSpace:"About this space",category:"Category:",rulesForThisSpace:"Space rules from the admin"},spaceTypeInfo:{default:{label:"Space type",popoverContent1:"Select a space type to see details.",popoverContent2:"",popoverTitle:"Space Type"},inviteOnly:{label:"Invite-only",popoverContent1:"Members must be invited and cannot request to join.",popoverContent2:"Only members of the space can view other members and content.",popoverTitle:"Invite-only Spaces"},private:{label:"Private",popoverContent1:"Anyone can request to join.",popoverContent2:"Only members of the space can view other members and content.",popoverTitle:"Private Spaces"},public:{label:"Public",popoverContent1:"Anyone can join.",popoverContent2:"Anyone can view other members and content.",popoverTitle:"Public Spaces"}}},spaceDetailPage:{loadingSpace:"Loading a space..."},spaceViewPage:{description:"View a Space",title:"View Spaces"},spaceYourSpacesTab:{emptyState:{createSpace:"Create a space",joinOrCreateSpace:"Join or create a space to get started.",noSpacesFound:"No spaces found"},filterOptions:{allSpaces:"All spaces",spacesYouJoined:"Spaces you've joined",spacesYouManage:"Spaces you manage"},labels:{view:"View"},loading:{loadingYourSpaces:"Loading your spaces...",refreshingYourSpaces:"Refreshing your spaces..."},search:{ariaLabel:"Search your spaces",placeholder:"Search your spaces..."}},title:"Spaces"},topicsAgenticAIPage:{authStatusAll:{breadcrumb:{labelFour:"Agentic AI",labelThree:"Topics",labelTwo:"Learn"},hero:{subTitle:"Build, deploy, and scale AI agents with AWS.",title:"Agentic AI"},sectionBuildingAIAgents:{bodyFour:"Kiro brings the latest agentic experience to the CLI provides a more dynamic, interactive coding experience that works with you, and iteratively makes changes based on your feedback.",bodyOne:"Learn what AI Agents are, including how it works, key components and types, benefits, challenges, and more.",bodyThree:"Explore how to start using agentic coding through your IDE.",bodyTwo:"This guidance demonstrates how to leverage generative AI to enhance operational efficiencies and drive innovation for energy organizations.",ctaFour:"Read the announcement",ctaOne:"Learn more",ctaThree:"Read the announcement",ctaTwo:"Read the article",labelFour:"Blog",labelOne:"Guide",labelThree:"Blog",labelTwo:"Guide",title:"Building AI Agents on AWS",titleFour:"Agentic coding experience in a CLI",titleOne:"What are AI Agents?",titleThree:"Agentic coding experience in your IDE",titleTwo:"Agentic Workflow Assistants on AWS"},sectionDiveDeepStrands:{body:"An open source SDK that takes a model-driven approach to building and running AI agents in just a few lines of code.",bodyFive:"Learn how to use different AI models with the Strands Agents SDK, including models from Amazon Bedrock and OpenAI, as well as local models with Ollama.",bodyFour:"In Part 3 we'll integrate the Model Context Protocol (MCP) to connect our agent with external specialized services. You'll learn how to expand your agent's capabilities by connecting to any MCP server with just a few lines of code.",bodyOne:"Create your first AI agent using Strands Agents SDK and Amazon Bedrock with minimal code. Learn to set up your environment and build a subject expert agent as the initial step in our Integrated Learning Lab project.",bodyThree:"Learn to connect your AI agent to the real world using built-in and custom tools. This tutorial explores Strands SDK's built-in tools and teaches you to create custom ones, transforming your conversational agent into a truly useful assistant.",bodyTwo:"Create your first AI agent using Strands Agents SDK and Amazon Bedrock with minimal code. Learn to set up your environment and build a subject expert agent as the initial step in our Integrated Learning Lab project.",ctaFive:"Start part 4 ",ctaFour:"Start part 3",ctaOne:"Start part 1",ctaThree:"Start part 2",ctaTwo:"Start part 1",labelFive:"Tutorial",labelFour:"Tutorial",labelOne:"Tutorial",labelThree:"Tutorial",labelTwo:"Tutorial",title:"Dive Deeper with Strands Agents",titleFive:"Building AI Agents with Strands: Part 4 - Alternative Model Providers",titleFour:"Building AI Agents with Strands: Part 3 - MCP Integration",titleOne:"Building AI Agents with Strands: Part 1 - Creating Your First Agent",titleThree:"Building AI Agents with Strands: Part 2 - Tool Integration",titleTwo:"Building AI Agents with Strands: Part 1 - Creating Your First Agent"},sectionGetStartedPython:{body:"Whether you are using Python or Java, you can build your AI agents using open source frameworks / libraries and run them on AWS.",bodyOne:"This quickstart guide shows you how to create your first basic Strands agent, add built-in and custom tools to your agent, use different model providers, emit debug logs, and run the agent locally.",bodyThree:"Learn how to use LangGraph and Mistral models on Amazon Bedrock to create a powerful multi-agent system that can handle sophisticated workflows through collaborative problem-solving.",bodyTwo:"Learn from Spring AI-based Java code examples how to run Model Context Protocol (MCP) clients & servers on AWS, using Amazon Bedrock and Amazon ECS.",ctaOne:"Read the guide ",ctaThree:"Start the tutorial ",ctaTwo:"Start the tutorial ",labelOne:"QuickStart Guide",labelThree:"Tutorial",labelTwo:"Tutorial",title:"Get Started in Python or Java",titleOne:"Getting Started with Strands Agents",titleThree:"Build a Multi-Agent System with LangGraph and Mistral on AWS",titleTwo:"Running MCP-Based Agents (Clients & Servers) on AWS with Java and Spring AI"},sectionIntroducingStrands:{bodyOne:"Agent frameworks getting in your way? Meet Strands Agents, an open source Python SDK that takes a model-driven approach to building and running AI agents in just a few lines of code.",ctaOneA:"Read launch article ",ctaOneB:"Watch video",titleOne:"Introducing Strands Agents"},sectionOpenProtocolsAgents:{body:"Agentic AI represents a shift from reactive to proactive AI systems that make informed decisions and take independent actions. AI agents access tools, data, and the internet while navigating complex tasks across industries. Multiple open protocols have emerged to enable agent interoperability.",bodyOne:"MCP is an open protocol that standardizes how applications provide context to large language models (LLMs), proposed by Anthropic. Acting as a universal connector for AI applications, it enables seamless integration between LLMs and various data sources and tools. AWS has joined the MCP steering committee and is excited to evolve the protocol together with the developer community.",bodyThree:"Learn how AWS is enhancing the Model Context Protocol (MCP) for better agent-to-agent communication. Explore how features like human-in-the-loop, streaming results, and capability discovery are improving inter-agent collaboration.",bodyTwo:"In this video, Mike Chambers, Sr. Developer Advocate at AWS, explains the ins and outs of MCP. Explore how MCP decouples agents from servers, allowing for seamless integration with cloud-based resources and remote functionality.",ctaOne:"Explore on GitHub",ctaThree:"Read the article",ctaTwo:"Watch the video",labelOne:"Repository",labelThree:"Blog post",labelTwo:"Video",title:"Open Protocols for Agent Interoperability",titleOne:"Model Context Protocol (MCP)",titleThree:"Inter-Agent Communication on MCP",titleTwo:"What is MCP? No, Really!"},sectionQuickLinks:{ctaFour:"Agentic AI with AWS Code Samples",ctaOne:"Open Source Strands Agents Python SDK",ctaThree:"Spring AI with Amazon Bedrock",ctaTwo:"Building Agents with AWS: Complete Tutorial (Java, Spring AI, Amazon Bedrock & MCP) ",title:"Quick Links"}}},topicsDeveloperToolsPage:{authStatusAll:{breadcrumb:{labelFour:"Developer Tools",labelThree:"Topics",labelTwo:"Learn"},hero:{subTitle:"AWS provides a comprehensive suite of developer tools that streamline your development and deployment. SDKs for popular programming languages, CLI tools, and the AI-powered Kiro for intelligent code suggestions, all help you write + deploy code faster.",title:"Developer Tools"},sectionAppIntegration:{body:"Our Getting Started documentation provides a structured learning path, beginning with fundamental AWS concepts and gradually progressing you to hands-on implementation of cloud services. You will find step-by-step instructions for creating your first AWS project, complete with practical examples and best practices that help them understand core services like compute, storage, and databases.",bodyOne:"Managed GraphQL service to build real-time and offline mobile/web apps.",bodyThree:"Coordinate distributed applications and automate workflows visually.",bodyTwo:"Service for creating, publishing, maintaining, and securing APIs.",ctaOne:"Get started",ctaThree:"Get started",ctaTwo:"Get started",labelOne:"Tutorial",labelThree:"Tutorial",labelTwo:"Tutorial",title:"Application Integration"},sectionContIntDel:{body:"Developer ToolContinuous Integration and Delivery (CI/CD) streamlines a developer's workflow by automatically building, testing, and deploying code changes as they're committed to the repository. This automation significantly reduces manual errors, catches bugs early in the development cycle, and eliminates the stress of complex manual deployments.",bodyFive:"Service to automate provisioning and deployment of microservices-based applications.",bodyFour:"Secure, managed Git repository hosting.",bodyOne:"Continuous integration and delivery service for automating release pipelines.",bodyThree:"Automated deployment service supporting applications to EC2, Lambda, ECS, and on-premises environments",bodyTwo:"Fully managed build service that compiles source code, runs tests, and produces deployment-ready packages.",ctaFive:"Get started",ctaFour:"Get started",ctaOne:"Get started",ctaThree:"Get started",ctaTwo:"Get started",title:"Continuous Integration and Delivery"},sectionFeed:{title:"Explore Content"},sectionInfraCode:{body:"Automatically build, test, and prepare software for release.",bodyOne:"Model and set up your AWS resources so that you can spend less time managing those resources and more time focusing on your applications that run in AWS.",bodyThree:"Use AWS CDK to put your infrastructure, application code, and configuration all in one place, ensuring that you have a complete, cloud-deployable system at every milestone.",bodyTwo:"Visualize, build, and deploy modern applications from all AWS services that are supported by AWS CloudFormation without needing to be an expert in AWS CloudFormation.",ctaOne:"Learn more",ctaThree:"Explore more",ctaTwo:"Learn more",title:"Infrastructure as Code"},sectionMonitoringObserv:{body:"Our Getting Started documentation provides a structured learning path, beginning with fundamental AWS concepts and gradually progressing you to hands-on implementation of cloud services. You will find step-by-step instructions for creating your first AWS project, complete with practical examples and best practices that help them understand core services like compute, storage, and databases.",bodyOne:"Observe and monitor resources and applications on AWS, on premises, and on other clouds.",bodyThree:"AWS Config is a service that enables you to assess, audit, and evaluate the configurations of your AWS resources.",bodyTwo:"Track user activity and API usage on AWS and in hybrid and multicloud environments.",ctaOne:"Learn more",ctaThree:"Learn more",ctaTwo:"Learn more",title:"Monitoring & Observability"},sectionQDeveloper:{body:"Kiro is an agentic IDE and CLI that helps you do your best work with features such as specs, steering, and hooks. Begin your journey with Kiro in under 5 minutes.",cta:"Get started",label:"Coding assistant"},sectionQuickLinks:{ctaFive:"DevOps info",ctaFour:"Developer Tools info",ctaOne:"Open Source AWS Samples",ctaThree:"Developer Tools Blog",ctaTwo:"What are Developer Tools?",title:"Quick links"},sectionWritingCodeAWS:{body:"AWS provides a comprehensive tooling environment that streamlines your software development process. With these SDKs and tools you can create apps in the language you love and allow our SDKs to interact with the AWS APIs for you.",bodyFive:"Build fullstack apps with your framework of choice, including React, Next.js, Angular, Vue, and more.",bodyFour:"Simplified framework for building serverless applications on AWS Lambda.",bodyOne:"Libraries supporting languages: JavaScript, Python, Java, .NET, Ruby, PHP, Go, Swift, C++, Rust, Kotlin, etc.",bodyThree:"Extensions for popular IDEs (VS Code, JetBrains, Visual Studio) offering integrated AWS access.",bodyTwo:"Framework for defining cloud infrastructure using familiar languages like TypeScript, Python, Java, and C#.",ctaFive:"Learn more",ctaFour:"Learn more",ctaOne:"Learn more",ctaThree:"Clone Repository",ctaTwo:"Learn more",labelFive:"Front End Development",labelFour:"Back End Development",labelOne:"Developer Tools",labelThree:"Developer Tools",labelTwo:"Developer Tools",title:"Writing Code on AWS"}}},topicsNosqlPage:{authStatusAll:{breadcrumb:{labelFour:"nosql",labelThree:"Topics",labelTwo:"Learn"},hero:{subTitle:"Build high-performance apps at scale with NoSQL databases on AWS.",title:"NoSQL databases"},sectionCallToAction:{ctaPrimary:"Create your AWS account",ctaSecondary:"Explore AWS Free Tier",description:"Explore what AWS Free Tier offers for AWS NoSQL database services, then sign up for your AWS Account to start building database solutions.",title:"Start building NoSQL databases with AWS"},sectionDatabaseTypes:{description:"NoSQL databases (also known as non-relational databases) are purpose-built for specific use cases. AWS offers services for six types: key-value, document, graph, in-memory (persistent and cache), and search.",document:{cta:"Amazon DocumentDB resources",description:"Document databases store semi-structured JSON data that adapts with applications, supporting catalogs, user profiles, and content management. AWS offers this via Amazon DocumentDB.",title:"Document",whenToAvoid:"It is not recommended if you need automatic horizontal scaling or simple key-value access.",whenToAvoidLabel:"When to avoid:",whenToUse:"Use when migrating from MongoDB or need MongoDB compatibility, you need complex queries on document fields and nested data, your data has hierarchical nested structures, you require ACID transactions within documents, or you want a serverless option for variable workloads.",whenToUseLabel:"When to use:"},graph:{cta:"Amazon Neptune resources",description:"Graph databases model complex relationships in highly connected data for social networking, recommendation engines, and fraud detection. AWS delivers this via Amazon Neptune.",title:"Graph",whenToAvoid:"It is not recommended if your data doesn't have complex relationships or you need simple queries.",whenToAvoidLabel:"When to avoid:",whenToUse:"Use when your data is highly connected (social networks, fraud detection), you need to traverse relationships efficiently, you're building recommendation engines or knowledge graphs, you need both property graph (Gremlin) and RDF (SPARQL) support, or you require graph algorithms for analytics.",whenToUseLabel:"When to use:"},inMemoryCache:{cta:"Amazon ElastiCache resources",description:"In-memory caching services eliminate disk access to deliver sub-millisecond response times for leaderboards, session stores, and real-time analytics. AWS provides this via Amazon ElastiCache.",title:"In-memory (Cache)",whenToAvoid:"It is not recommended if you need persistent storage or complex data relationships.",whenToAvoidLabel:"When to avoid:",whenToUse:"Use when you require sub-millisecond latency for frequently accessed data, you're implementing caching layers or session stores, you need Redis or Memcached compatibility, you want to reduce load on primary databases, or you're building real-time applications (gaming, chat).",whenToUseLabel:"When to use:"},inMemoryPersistent:{cta:"Amazon MemoryDB resources",description:"In-memory databases provide Redis-compatible microsecond response times for leaderboards, session stores, and real-time analytics with durability guarantees. AWS offers this via Amazon MemoryDB.",title:"In-memory (Persistent)",whenToAvoid:"It is not recommended if you don't need Redis compatibility or have cost constraints.",whenToAvoidLabel:"When to avoid:",whenToUse:"Use when you need Redis compatibility with durability guarantees, you're building microservices that need fast persistent data, you need both caching and primary database functionality, you require strong consistency with microsecond latency, or you want to simplify architecture by eliminating separate cache layers.",whenToUseLabel:"When to use:"},keyValue:{cta:"Amazon DynamoDB resources",description:"Key-value databases store data as pairs with unique identifiers, enabling high partition ability and horizontal scaling beyond other NoSQL types. AWS provides this via Amazon DynamoDB.",title:"Key-value",whenToAvoid:"It is not recommended if you need complex queries, joins, or ad-hoc analytics.",whenToAvoidLabel:"When to avoid:",whenToUse:"Key-value databases work when you require single-digit millisecond latency with well-defined access patterns (get/put by key). This type is good when building event-driven or microservices architectures, when using serverless with automatic scaling, and when global tables for multi-region applications are needed.",whenToUseLabel:"When to use:"},search:{cta:"Amazon OpenSearch resources",description:"Search databases index and analyze unstructured logs and metrics for near-real-time insights and data visualization. AWS delivers this via Amazon OpenSearch.",title:"Search",whenToAvoid:"It is not recommended if you only need simple key-value lookups or transactional consistency.",whenToAvoidLabel:"When to avoid:",whenToUse:"Use when you need full-text search with relevance scoring, you're building search experiences or log analytics, you need real-time data visualization dashboards, you require complex aggregations and filtering, or you want a serverless option for cost optimization.",whenToUseLabel:"When to use:"},title:"NoSQL database types & services"},sectionQuickLinks:{ctaFive:"AWS Well-Architected Framework",ctaFour:"Compare database services",ctaOne:"AWS Database Demos",ctaSix:"Setting up AWS Account",ctaThree:"Databases on AWS",ctaTwo:"AWS Database Blog",title:"Quick links"},sectionResourcesToLearn:{cardFive:{cta:"Start tutorial",description:"Implement CQRS pattern with DynamoDB for writes and OpenSearch for complex queries. Includes data synchronization strategies.",label:"Intermediate",title:"Create a search application with Amazon OpenSearch Service"},cardFour:{cta:"Start tutorial",description:"Implement CQRS pattern with DynamoDB for writes and OpenSearch for complex queries. Includes data synchronization strategies.",label:"Intermediate",title:"Create a search application with Amazon OpenSearch Service"},cardOne:{cta:"Start learning",description:"Learn fundamentals of managed noSQL database services. The digital training included in this Learning Plan will expose you to AWS nonrelational database services.",label:"Foundational",title:"NoSQL Foundational Learning Plan"},cardSeven:{cta:"Start tutorial",description:"Advanced DynamoDB optimization techniques including hot partition detection, capacity planning, and cost optimization.",label:"Advanced",title:"Using the DynamoDB Well-Architected Lens"},cardSix:{cta:"Start tutorial",description:"Implement Redis caching to improve application performance and reduce database load with session management and data caching patterns.",label:"Intermediate",title:"Create a Redis OSS serverless cache"},cardThree:{cta:"Start tutorial",description:"Configure Docker Compose with DynamoDB Local, Redis, and MongoDB for offline development and testing.",label:"Foundational",title:"Setting up DynamoDB local"},cardTwo:{cta:"Start tutorial",description:"Build a complete serverless application using DynamoDB, Lambda, and API Gateway. Perfect for developers new to NoSQL.",label:"Foundational",title:"Build a Basic Web Application"},description:"From foundational to advanced, start skill up on NoSQL databases.",title:"Resources to help you learn"},sectionStarterEssentials:{cardFive:{cta:"Read the article",description:"Strategic guide for NoSQL development tools covering data modeling, ORMs vs SDKs, Infrastructure as Code, local development, and monitoring.",label:"Article",title:"Tools and Frameworks for NoSQL Developer Productivity"},cardFour:{cta:"Read the article",description:"Strategic guide for NoSQL development tools covering data modeling, ORMs vs SDKs, Infrastructure as Code, local development, and monitoring.",label:"Article",title:"Tools and Frameworks for NoSQL Developer Productivity"},cardOne:{cta:"Read the article",description:"Practical guide for building NoSQL applications on AWS with data modeling, local development, deployment, and monitoring strategies for developers at all levels.",label:"Article",title:"Getting Started with AWS NoSQL"},cardSeven:{cta:"Explore solutions",description:"Explore the decision guide for databases to determine which AWS databases are the best fit for your organization.",label:"Solutions Library",title:"Database use cases and solutions"},cardSix:{cta:"Explore the guide",description:"Explore the decision guide for databases to determine which AWS databases are the best fit for your organization.",label:"Guide",title:"AWS Databases Decision Guide"},cardThree:{cta:"Read the article",description:"Practical guide to common NoSQL architecture patterns and service combinations across industries with proven multi-database strategies.",label:"Article",title:"AWS NoSQL Use Cases and Patterns"},cardTwo:{cta:"Read the article",description:"Systematic framework for selecting AWS NoSQL databases based on access patterns, performance needs, and operational constraints to optimize application architecture and costs.",label:"Article",title:"Strategic NoSQL Database Selection Framework"},title:"Your NoSQL database starter essentials"},sectionToolsToBuild:{cardOne:{cta:"Explore on GitHub",description:"Access cost optimization tools, migration utilities, capacity planning tools, table class optimizer, and more.",label:"Repository",title:"Amazon DynamoDB repository",url:"https://github.com/awslabs/amazon-dynamodb-tools"},cardThree:{cta:"Explore on GitHub",description:"Access migration tools, monitoring utilities, performance optimization scripts, sample applications, and more.",label:"Repository",title:"Amazon DocumentDB repository",url:"https://github.com/awslabs/amazon-documentdb-tools"},cardTwo:{cta:"Explore on GitHub",description:"Access graph application examples, query samples, ML integration demos, visualization examples, and more.",label:"Repository",title:"Amazon Neptune repository",url:"https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-neptune-samples"},description:"Dive into GitHub repositories for tools, examples, demos, sample applications, and more.",title:"Tools to help you build"}}},topicsServerlessPage:{authStatusAll:{breadcrumb:{labelFour:"Serverless",labelThree:"Topics",labelTwo:"Learn"},hero:{subTitle:"Build and run applications without thinking about servers",title:"Serverless"},sectionExploreServerless:{bodyFive:"Learn how GenAI guides serverless testing through better architecture. Live demos show evolving Lambda functions, generating scalable tests, and preventing technical debt with clean design patterns.",bodyFour:"Learn to use CloudWatch Logs Live Tail to identify and debug issues in the AWS Lambda functions. You'll also learn how to use the CloudWatch Logs Live Tail feature to tail the logs of up to five Lambda functions on the same screen as your code.",bodyOne:"Learn about AWS Lambda's local IDE experience to simplify application development. This can help you more easily author, build, debug, test, and deploy Lambda applications in your local IDE when using Visual Studio Code.",bodyThree:"Learn how to use variables to simplify data management across multiple states in AWS Step Functions. The step function variables reduce this complexity by offering variables that are stored outside of the states and available at each level of the state machine.",bodyTwo:"Explore the top 10 AWS Lambda Functions in the AWS Management Console by performance, errors, and concurrency. These functions identify the highest performing Lambda functions and the most notable bad actors in the console.",ctaFive:"Watch the video",ctaFour:"Watch the video",ctaOne:"Watch the video",ctaThree:"Watch the video",ctaTwo:"Watch the video",title:"Explore videos about Serverless",titleFive:"Supercharge Serverless testing: Accelerate development with Kiro",titleFour:"Debugging AWS Lambda Functions in Console with CloudWatch Logs Live Tail",titleOne:"AWS Lambda Local IDE Experience",titleThree:"Using Workflow Variables in AWS Step Function",titleTwo:"Top 10 AWS Lambda Functions in the Console"},sectionHandsOnServerless:{bodyFive:"Search for code repos you can use for examples, learning or building serverless applications. Filter by usecase, runtime, and level.",bodyFour:"Use AWS Step Functions workflows to quickly build applications using AWS SAM and CDK templates. Filter by usecase and copy the template or workflow definition directly into your application.",bodyOne:"This tutorial guides you through creating a serverless web app for requesting unicorn rides from Wild Rydes. You'll build a user interface for ride requests, implement user authentication, and connect to a RESTful backend service for dispatching unicorns.",bodyThree:"Use serverless patterns to quickly build integrations using AWS SAM and AWS CDK templates. Filter by pattern and copy the template directly into your application.",bodyTwo:"Learn to set up asynchronous messaging with Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS), enabling cloud-based communication between application components. Using the SQS console, you'll create a queue, send and receive messages, and manage the queue lifecycle.",ctaFive:"Explore more",ctaFour:"Explore more",ctaOne:"Start the tutorial",ctaThree:"Explore more",ctaTwo:"Start the tutorial",title:"Hands on Serverless",titleFive:"Sample applications",titleFour:"AWS Step Function workflows library",titleOne:"Build a Serverless Web Application",titleThree:"Serverless Patterns",titleTwo:"Send Messages Between Distributed Applications"},sectionQuickLinks:{ctaOne:"AWS Serverless Documentation",ctaThree:"AWS Lambda Documentation",ctaTwo:"Serverless Developer Guide",title:"Quick Links"},sectionServerlessLand:{body:"Explore extensive collections of serverless patterns, workflows, and code snippets, helping developers build scalable applications using fully-managed serverless architecture with services like AWS Lambda, Amazon EventBridge, and AWS Step Functions.",cta:"Explore more",title:"Serverless Land"}}},unsavedChangesModal:{cancelButton:"Cancel",header:"Leave page",leaveButton:"Leave",message:"Are you sure that you want to leave the current page? The changes that you made won't be saved."},unsupportedBrowser:{learnMore:"Learn more",message:"Use a browser supported by AWS Builder Center. {{learnMore}}",title:"Your browser is unsupported."},unsupportedBrowserVersion:{learnMore:"Learn more",message:"Update to a browser version supported by AWS Builder Center. {{learnMore}}",title:"Your browser version is unsupported."},wishCreatePage:{authStatusPostAuth:{breadcrumb:{labelThree:"Create a wish"},button:{cancel:"Cancel",submit:"Submit"},categoryField:{description:"Choose a category that best fits your wish.",errorMessage:"Category is a required field",placeholder:"Choose category",title:"Category"},descriptionField:{characterCount:"###/### characters",description:"Provide details to help others understand your wish.",errorMessage:"Description is a required field",markdown:"Markdown cheatsheet",placeholder:"What do you want to share?",title:"Description"},disclaimer:{description:"Please read and understand the AWS Builder Terms before creating content."},header:{description:"Provide details for service improvements or new functionality.",title:"Create a wish"},serviceField:{description:"Choose an AWS service.",errorMessage:"AWS service is a required field",placeholder:"Choose AWS service",title:"AWS Service"},tagsField:{description:"Add tags to your wish so it can be searched easily.",errorMessage:"Please reduce tag selection to 5 or less.",placeholder:"Select tags",results:"No tags found",tagCount:"5 maximum",title:"Tags"},titleField:{characterCount:"###/### characters",description:"This appears in search results and feeds. It should be short, descriptive, and unique.",errorMessage:"Title is a required field",header:"Title",placeholder:"Title"}}},wishPublishedComment:{authStatusPostAuth:{limitPopup:{closeAriaLabel:"Close quota modal",createLimitDescription:"Thanks for being an active contributor! You can post a new comment in 10 minutes.",createLimitTitle:"You've reached the create limit for comments"},moderatorView:{banner:"This content has been suspended by the moderator and is only visible to the content owner and moderators. If you think this was a mistake, please contact support.",buttonDropdownReport:"Report",buttonDropdownSuspend:"Suspend"},popupReport:{fieldQuestion:"Share any additional information that will help us understand and handle the situation - {{optionalLabel}}",moderationCancelCTA:"Cancel",moderationReportDescription:"What type of issue are you reporting?",optionalLabel:"optional",radioButtonEight:"Harassment content",radioButtonEleven:"Suicide or Self-Harm",radioButtonFive:"Sharing personal information or Privacy",radioButtonFour:"Account hacked/ impersonating",radioButtonNine:"Violent/extremist content",radioButtonOne:"Spam or misleading content",radioButtonSeven:"Fraud content",radioButtonSix:"Offensive content",radioButtonTen:"Child sexual abuse and exploitation",radioButtonThree:"AI-generated content",radioButtonTwelve:"Other reasons",radioButtonTwo:"Plagiarism content"},publishedComment:{awsBuilderTerms:"AWS Builder Terms",copyAltTextHover:"Copy comment",copyButton:"Link copied",description:"By commenting, you agree to the {{awsBuilderTerms}}.",hideRepliesCTA:"Hide replies",likeAltTextHover:"Like comment",moderationReportButton:"Report",replyCTA:"Reply",resultsSort:"Sort by",resultsSortDropdownNewest:"Newest",resultsSortDropdownOldest:"Oldest",resultsSortDropdownTop:"Top",showRepliesCTA:"Show replies",statementCommentEditLimit:"Editing is allowed only within 10 minutes of publishing your comment.",submitAltTextHover:"Submit comment",submitCTA:"Submit",threeDotsButtonAltTextHover:"Show more",title:"Comments ({{numberOfComments}})",updateCTA:"Update"},reportPopUp:{description:"What type of issue are you reporting?",placeholder:"Any additional information?",title:"Comment"},reportSubmission:{bannerReceipt:"This content has been reported successfully. A moderator will review and take appropriate action."}}},wishPublishedDetailsPage:{authStatusPostAuth:{alertBanner:{statusPublished:"Your wish has been published successfully 🎉"},moderatorView:{banner:"This content has been suspended by the moderator and is only visible to the content owner and moderators. If you think this was a mistake, please contact support.",buttonDropdownReport:"Report",buttonDropdownSuspend:"Suspend"},publishedComment:{buttonDropdownReport:"Report",ctaText:"Translate",description:"By commenting, you agree to the AWS Builder Terms.",publishDetail:"Published",resultsSort:"Sort by",resultsSortDropdownNewest:"Newest",resultsSortDropdownOldest:"Oldest",resultsSortDropdownTop:"Top",title:"Comments (#)"},publishedCommentTranslate:{annotation:"Content is machine-translated to the language selected in settings."},publishedDetail:{bannerSuccessfulUpdateWish:"Your updates have been saved.",buttonDropdownReport:"Report",buttonFollow:"Follow",publishDetail:"Published"},publishedTranslate:{annotation:"Content is machine-translated to the language selected in settings.",buttonDropdownReport:"Report",ctaText:"Translate"},reportPopUp:{description:"What type of issue are you reporting?",fieldQuestion:"Do you have any additional information that will help us understand and handle the situation? - optional",placeholder:"Any additional information?",selectAIGeneratedContent:"AI-generated content",selectAccountHackedImpersonating:"Account hacked/impersonating",selectChildSexualAbuseExploitation:"Child sexual abuse and exploitation",selectFraud:"Fraud",selectHarassment:"Harassment",selectOffensiveContent:"Offensive content",selectOther:"Other",selectPlagiarism:"Plagiarism",selectSharingPersonalPrivateInformation:"Sharing personal or private information",selectSpam:"Spam",selectSuicideSelfHarm:"Suicide/self-harm",selectViolentExtremistContent:"Violent/extremist content",title:"Report content"},reportSubmission:{bannerReceipt:"Your report has been submitted for moderator review."}}},wishlistPage:{authStatusPostAuth:{asideRecentActivity:{headline:"Recent activity"},discoverFeed:{ctaButton:"Show more"},discoverSort:{dropdownSortByTitle:"Sort by"},main:{tabDiscover:"Discover",tabYourWishlist:"Your wishlist"},page:{body:"Search, vote, or submit your own idea to help improve AWS.",ctaButton:"Create a wish"},tabFeedCard:{moderationReportButton:"Report"},tabFilterAWSService:{filterAWSServicePlaceholder:"AWS Service"},tabFilterCategory:{filterCategoryPlaceholder:"Category"},tabFilterStatus:{filterStatusPlaceholder:"Status"},yourWishlistFeed:{resultsEmptyStatusTitle:"No results found.",resultsFailStatusTitle:"Fail to load"}},authStatusPreAuth:{description:"Wishlist is a dedicated feedback forum within Builder Center for the AWS community to influence product and service roadmaps. Wishlist allows builders to submit ideas, suggestions, or challenges they face while using AWS products and services.",fakeWish:{descriptionFull:"I want to be able to easily collaborate and share knowledge with other builders working on similar technologies or use cases. The current fragmented community experience across different AWS properties makes it difficult to find and engage with peers who share my interests. The feature would allow me and other AWS builders to:\n\n• Create and join specialized groups focused on specific topics or technologies\n• Allow creating open or private groups\n• Share content, ask questions, and engage in discussions within these groups\n• Build meaningful connections with others working on similar challenges\n• Manage membership and content moderation for spaces I create\n• Discover relevant spaces through search and recommendations\n• Get notifications about activity in groups I'm part of\n\nThis would help the community solve several pain points: \n• Difficulty finding other developers working on similar AWS technologies\n• Fragmented community discussions spread across different experiences\n• Limited ability to build sustained collaborations around specific topics\n• Solve for the challenge of knowledge sharing across the broader AWS community\n\nHaving these functionality would make AWS Builder Center much more valuable as a community platform and help developers like me get more value from AWS through peer collaboration and knowledge sharing.",title:"Enable community collaboration in AWS Builder Center"},hero:{body:"Have an idea to share? Create, discuss, and vote for AWS product and feature improvements.",ctaButtonOne:"Create a wish",ctaButtonTwo:"How it works"},signInWishlist:{body:"Join AWS Builder Center to vote and discuss wishes created by AWS builders, or submit